[1
Date: Sat, 25 Jul 1998 19:19:34 -0400
Source: News media
Via: George A. Robertson <grobertson@erols.com>

Wisconsin officials said Friday that they have identified at least four
people who took part in a Madison triathlon on July 5 and who later
developed symptoms of leptospirosis. [Note *symptoms* not serology or other
diagnostic evidence of infection. Laboratory tests have yet to be
completed. Wisconsin health officials say they now are more than halfway
through their effort to contact 279 Wisconsin residents who may have been
exposed to the disease [infection at two recent triathlons, one in Madison
on July 5 and another in Springfield, Ill., on June 21.
A total of 966 people took part in the Springfield race. About 850 people
competed in the Madison race, which held its swim portion in Lake Wingra.
It is likely that more people who took part in just the Madison event, and
who developed symptoms will be found, said Jeff Davis, chief medical
officer and state epidemiologist for communicable diseases with the state
Division of Health. [See below for comments by JD Diagnostic symptoms
include a fever AND two of the following -- chills, headache, muscle ache,
abdominal pain, red eyes and a rash; it is treated with common antibiotics.
"Even if one of those (four from the Madison triathlon) has leptospirosis,
that would be significant," Davis said.
So far, 74 people who may have contracted leptospirosis from participating
in either of the two triathlons have been identified by officials with the
U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Sixty-four of those
individuals were in only the Springfield event, four did just the Madison
event and six participated in both events. Of the 74 who are believed to
have had the disease, 54 sought medical attention and 21 of those were
hospitalized.
[Written by John Fauber
